President Joseph R. Biden, Jr. will be visiting the Republic of Korea and Japan from May 20 to May 24. The purpose of the trip is to strengthen ties between the United States and these countries. The visit will focus on the Biden-Harris Administration's commitment to a free and open Indo-Pacific region, as well as the U.S. treaty alliances with the Republic of Korea and Japan. President Biden will hold bilateral meetings with President Yoon Suk Yeol of the Republic of Korea and Prime Minister Kishida Fumio of Japan. The discussions will cover areas such as security relationships, economic ties, and cooperation in delivering practical results. Additionally, President Biden will also meet with the leaders of the Quad grouping, which includes Australia, Japan, India, and the United States. More details about the trip will be shared soon.